# Security Reviews — batta MCP

This repository uses [batta](https://github.com/batta-ai/batta-ai) for structured security
reviews. The batta MCP server is configured in `.claude/mcp.json`.

**Do not call the HTTP endpoint directly. Use the MCP tools through your agent.**

## Before implementing any feature

1. Check whether this repository has been indexed:

   ```
   get_indexing_status
   ```

   If `status` is not `"completed"` or coverage is 0, run `/batta-index` first and
   finish the indexing workflow before feature work when possible.

2. Start a security review before writing any implementation code for every new feature,
   behavior change, endpoint, data flow, integration, auth change, storage change,
   infrastructure change, or dependency change:

   ```
   /batta-review <one-sentence description of the change>
   ```

   or without the slash command:

   > Start a batta security review for: \<description\>

   The full protocol is injected automatically. Do not skip any step.

## Task severity guide

| Severity | Required action |
| --- | --- |
| critical | Must address before merging |
| high | Must address; document explicitly if deferred |
| medium | Should address; defer with written justification |
| low | Best effort |

## Architecture baseline note

After `submit_security_answers`, study `featureSecurityContext` carefully — it contains
the existing DFDs, threat models, and data classifications that are the baseline for your
change. When calling `submit_security_attestations`, `architectureUpdates` must include the
**complete** state of each entry after your change, not just the delta.

## Attestation evidence rules

Every submitted attestation must reference concrete evidence such as files, symbols,
routes, tests, migrations, config keys, or documentation. Do not include secrets, tokens,
private keys, `.env` values, or raw source blobs.
